#
#  seahorse distinctive features:
#    - APP + COMMAND TYPES — `App::new(name)` for top-level,
#      `Command::new(name)` for subcommands; both have chainable
#      builders for `description/author/version/usage/action/flag/
#      command`
#    - CHAINED-BUILDER FLUENT API similar in style to commander.js
#      / kingpin / clap-builder — successor methods return Self
#      for chaining: `App::new(...).description(...).flag(...)
#      .command(...).run(args)`
#    - FLAG TYPES: `FlagType::Bool` (boolean), `FlagType::String`
#      (string-valued), `FlagType::Int` (signed integer),
#      `FlagType::Float` (f64), `FlagType::Uint` (unsigned int)
#    - `Flag::new(name, type)` builder + `.description(...)` +
#      `.alias("short")` for single-char short flag aliases
#    - `Command::new(name)` for subcommands + `.alias(...)` for
#      subcommand aliases (note: aliases can be MULTI-CHAR
#      including hyphenated forms like `"--file"`)
#    - `Context` passed to action handlers exposes
#      `bool_flag/string_flag/int_flag/float_flag/uint_flag`
#      query methods that return `bool` (for bool flags) or
#      `Result<T, FlagError>` (for value-bearing flags)
#    - `Context.args: Vec<String>` for positional arguments
#    - `.action(fn(&Context))` registers the handler function
#      pointer
#    - AUTO --help / -h / --version / -v generation from App
#      metadata
#    - Nested subcommands via Command::command() (subcommands can
#      have their own subcommands recursively — Cobra-style tree)
#    - INSPIRED BY spf13/cobra (Go) — Keisuke Toyota wrote
#      seahorse to bring Cobra's builder-pattern + subcommand-tree
#      ergonomics into Rust without clap's compile-time-derive
#      weight
#  Distinct from R275 Rust clap-derive (proc-macro #[derive(Parser)]
